The index was already down before the vote, but once it was revealed that the House of Representatives had not passed the bill, the index started to drop.
Congress backed down, so the U.S. government could pump $700 billion into the banks.
The top leaders of the U.S. Congress and the administration of President George W. Bush have agreed on a broader agreement and financial assistance for the U.S. financial system.
That's going to be voted on early next week.
U.S. lawmakers have made a breakthrough in negotiations to approve a bailout plan in the form of $700 billion in financial assistance to the U.S. financial system.
But it's not a victory yet.
Congress must finalize some of the details of the agreement before it can publish the final version of the bill and vote on it.
The financial system bailout bill is being debated in the House of Representatives on Monday.
This was reported by Barney Frank, chairman of the Financial Services Committee, to Reuters on Sunday.
Senate sources say the bill is likely to be voted on Wednesday at the earliest.
Economists say there should be an announcement that the bailout plan is approved, which is the first major psychological factor in reviving financial markets.
However, due to the complexity of the mechanisms, a "clean-up" takes place afterwards.
The plan must be effective.
"We've made a big step.
We have resolved our differences about what the shape of the market stabilization package should be", said Democratic Speaker Nancy Pelosi.
He says the final vote could be on Sunday.
Lawmakers met with Henry Paulson, the U.S. Treasury Secretary, Saturday night to finalize a new government fund.
It should buy up unsellable mortgage assets from financial corporations, which are causing financial corporations to incur serious losses and jeopardise the stability of the entire system.
'We are close to a final agreement on a design that will work and that must be effective in the market.
The corrective plan has yet to be completed, but I think we are there", said Paulson.
Signal to Asian trade
