Senator Harry Reid, a Democrat from Nevada, said lawmakers are now trying to get a deal through Congress by Sunday.
The move is intended to reassure investors before the Asian financial markets open, where the time zone is the first thing Congress will decide on Monday.
But it's not clear when the two chambers of Congress will vote on the bill, nor whether the hearing will be held at the last minute.
Lawmakers are hoping to get the bill passed in the next few days.
However, the law is still undergoing a number of changes.
The total amount to be allocated to the scheme shall be divided into two parts.
At the request of President George Bush, the first $350 billion should be available as soon as possible.
But Congress can block the release of the remaining $100 billion, and then $350 billion, if it feels the program is not doing its job.
Bush praised the progress in the negotiations.
While the president can veto this resolution, Congress can override its veto.
Despite these changes, however, the basic idea of the program remained to acquire financial assets to buy bad mortgage securities that were losing value because hundreds of thousands of Americans were unable to pay their mortgages.
"We worked it all out.
