Marek says it's not so important whether the plan is approved now or early next week.
"It is more important that Congress decide this week to support the plan and give its blessing as soon as possible.
The spiritual importance of getting agreement on the approval of the plan is the most important thing at the moment,' Marek stressed.
Couple of knife fights, MP3 players versus cell phones.
We'll help you choose
While almost all cell phones can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can be used to make phone calls.
It seems clear that it's better to just buy a phone.
Still, there are many reasons why people might want to get a separate MP3 player.
The choice is entirely dependent on the use and the needs of the prospective owner.
You're probably having a hard time getting a high-end, expensive record player to play that latest Maxim Turbulence record.
First, such music products do not appear on Bakelite records, but there is no objective reason for this in terms of quality.
However, if your shelves are full of art rock, jazz, or blues records, you probably dream of a record player like this.
It's similar to traveling, which is compressed -- simplified to MP3 music.
There are also price and quality categories.
For some it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns on a player, just as a Pink Floyd fan may find it difficult to accept a 20-crown headset on the market.
Two extremes, with enough room for everyone.
We have a wide choice.
Battery life is also important.
Some high-quality music players are capable of much more than just playing music, but they also do what most cell phones don't even happen to be capable of.
No modern device is as universal as the telephone.
In addition to the basic functions of calling and texting, it can play music and video, record both, has a camera, a camera, and even a navigation system.
And if you factor in smartphones and communicators, you'll have a little computer in your pocket.
It's a bit of a miracle, because no refrigerator can grill and no TV can take pictures.
But there are disadvantages to multifunctional cell phones.
The more functions you use on your phone, the more times the display sends it to the charger.
And playing music is one of the biggest energy-consuming activities.
Few mobile devices can play music for more than ten to twelve hours, usually much less.
In this respect, music players (especially the simplest ones) are significantly more powerful.
So, with cheap cell phones, you can expect them to play for you for no more than a few hours.
If you are also using your phone, get a charger for safety at work - even for more expensive devices.
You won't have this problem with MP3 players, even the worst ones can last at least nine hours of continuous operation on a single charge.
The next problem is uploading music to your mobile.
Unfortunately, only a limited number of devices have a universal USB connector and not all of them can be connected directly to a computer without special software.
Of course, music can be recorded directly onto the memory card, but few card readers can handle the miniature memory cards used in cell phones without an adapter.
With a few exceptions (iPod), players do not require any special software.
All you have to do is charge the device with music from your computer via USB.
Most mobile phones and players already create their own music library, sorted by artist, album, genre, or user rating.
Some devices only render a bit like Windows Explorer, and some know both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with operating system).
Players are easier to manage, phones know more
When choosing a particular device, you should first consider the battery life, memory capacity, quality and type of sound output, and of course the ease of use.
If you are primarily a background musician and only listen to music for a short time a day, such as on the tram, any mobile phone with an MP3 player is fine.
And any cell phone can do that.
You don't even have to pay attention to the music formats your phone or your player can play.
MP3s are all they can handle, and the vast majority of music that comes to you will be in that format.
MP3 is one of the most common formats, and most other devices can handle WMA music.
AAC (the format used by Apple and its iPod) is less common.
Better cell phones also make it possible, for example, to buy music online.
All you have to do is visit the relevant websites of the provider (or other provider) via the mobile internet and buy the song or album.
This service alone could be a compelling argument for buying a music phone.
Unfortunately, the service providers' offerings are meager and usually limited to one-year radio camps.
The prices are also the lowest.
However, it is generally assumed that this kind of music sales (whether via GSM, the Internet or wireless Internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people carry their mobile devices with them all the time.
Whenever he wants to listen to something, he's gonna go check his cell phone in his pocket while his forgotten MP3 player is at home.
However, it also depends on whether you always carry your earphones or at least your speakers.
If not, you can use the built-in speaker, which is available on almost all mobile phones but only on a few MP3 players.
For many people, the biggest advantage of music phones is probably the price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than three thousand crowns.
Between three and four thousand crowns, you can get a decent walkman.
But most of the time, you're limited by the lack of output from a traditional earpiece.
The best and most technically equipped phones can cost up to 15 000 kroner with traditional 3.5 mm diameter earphones.
The players' advantage is, however, among other things, the ease of use.
The simplest - not necessarily the cheapest - players (see our selection) are really something that everyone can handle.
Minimal function, the previously conventional cassette tape recorder or gramophone-like handling is obvious.
There is no threat of a crash in the form of accidentally switched on mobile Internet, nor of the enormous data bill that follows.
What to Choose
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for interchangeable memory cards (M2, microSD type, etc.).
With the right credit card, you can get up to two thousand crowns.
But be careful.
The default types only support cards with a maximum capacity of up to 2 GB.
Only the most expensive ones know what to do with 8GB of memory cards.
If you already have a cell phone and you want to buy a cheap MP3 player, choose Cowson, Creative, Sony, Samsung, Emgton or Iriver.
Based on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you don't have to spend more than 1 100 kroner.
If you are a more demanding student, choose a special mobile walkman (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
