The first virtual service provider will be available in the Czech Republic later this year.
Maybe I should
The Czech mobile market is relatively developed and our operators offer practically the same services as their Western European counterparts.
However, we are missing something here - a virtual service provider that forces traditional providers to make substantial price reductions.
Maybe it won't be like this for long.
We have written on Mobil.cz many times that Czech providers are among the most expensive in Europe.
This was confirmed by the ČTÚ, which pointed out that the price of SMS in the Czech Republic is more expensive than in the rest of the Union.
The latest move by the European Commission to regulate roaming charges may lead to a controversial situation - some Czech mobile phone operators will have cheaper SMS calls from abroad than domestic ones.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there's no competition that really wants to fight.
This may sound contradictory, because we have three cell networks and we have a penetration rate well above 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators are happy to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
This is often agreed by Pavel Dvořák, Chairman of the Board of the Czech Telecommunications Authority, who has previously stated several times that there is no room for a new operator in the Czech Republic.
It is perhaps true that the traditional operator with its own network would probably no longer have many opportunities (although it would probably find it difficult to find frequencies).
But there's another option - the virtual service provider.
It was the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that led to a significant price decrease, which was then also met by traditional operators.
Meanwhile, even before big fish like Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the market, there were voices like ours in the UK.
However, it has been shown that such providers have a place and can be really successful.
However, we do not have to go far to find an example.
In February this year, we informed you about the launch of the mobile virtual service provider Mobilking in Poland.
In less than six months, the service provider managed to acquire more than 100 000 customers and become the fifth largest service provider in the country.
Mobilking is, meanwhile, backed by the Penta financial group, which owns U:fon in the Czech Republic, among others.
The advantage of virtual service providers is that they can target a much narrower target group.
The Commission therefore concludes that the measure at issue is compatible with the internal market.
It does not entail relatively high construction, mobile network operation and maintenance costs.
Virtual service providers in the world thus generally appear to be low-cost - offering cheap calls and SMS, but often offsetting this with fewer services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS services at a minimum of 50% cheaper than its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, betting on such a target group can be a good move.
This service is specifically targeted at men.
"Real men choose Mobilking - a service they like and trust", says David Seibert, CEO of Mobil Entertainment Company, which operates the virtual service.
It is difficult to say whether a similar idea to Poland will work here.
The Commission notes that the Czech Republic has not provided any evidence that the measure was necessary to achieve the objective of common interest.
In addition, it is relatively satisfied with the services it provides.'
No chance in the Czech Republic, mobile operators say
However, it seems almost certain that if there is to be a virtual service provider in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about a successful expansion of this project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not look very promising.
The launch of Mobilking will take place in other countries in our region", Jana Studničková, spokesperson for Penta's financial group, told Mobil.cz in a telephone interview.
The Commission therefore concludes that the measure is imputable to the State.
On the contrary, they do their utmost to ensure that no potential competition arises.
GTS Novera has long been keen to launch the virtual service provider, which it intends to take a further step towards making Telefónica O2 a real competitor in the corporate customer market.
'We are very interested in providing our customers not only with wired but also with mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner the better.
We have re-negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
Some of them have already made progress in the negotiations", says Pavel Kaidl, spokesman for the group.
Maybe better times are coming.
From unofficial information, it looks like we might have a chance with the first virtual service provider by the end of the year.
But at the moment, his birth is surrounded by a wall of impenetrable silence.
'At the moment we do not think that a full-fledged virtual service provider has a place on the Czech market.
The Czech market is very special, unlike other markets.
So far, we have not been contacted by a single entity with a complex and serious project in this area", Vlastimil Sršeň, from Telefónica 02's press department, told Mobil.cz.
The special situation of the Czech market is also referred to by other providers.
Martina Kemrová, a spokesperson for T-Mobile, exceptionally agrees with O2, adding: 'We have not yet identified a viable and mutually beneficial business project on which to build further.'
And he added, "It's unlikely that any virtual service providers will be on the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
We should have a concrete agreement on the table right now to think about this short-term".
The Commission notes that the Commission has not yet decided whether the measure is compatible with the internal market.
Miroslav Čepický adds: 'We are open to negotiations with potential virtual service providers, especially in the area of cost and infrastructure sharing.
From a customer's perspective, that's what we consider the most rewarding.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find partners for the deployment of shared networks for high-speed mobile internet.'
Responsible offices - on the same page as service providers
The behaviour of mobile operators is easy to understand, the entry of a new operator would mean increased competition, lower prices and thus a decrease in their profits.
So why make it easier for a competitor like that to get in?
When service providers are able to work together on something important, the link around the birth of U:fon is also evident.
The greatest pressure on ČTU was probably felt around the birth of the T-Mobile U:phone.
This is evidenced by the publicly available information on the CTU website.
But right now, U:fon is a good argument for why we shouldn't allow the virtual service provider in.
Martina Kemrová added: 'The competitive environment in the mobile market has recently been weakened by the entry of the fourth mobile operator.
In view of the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is clear that the entry of a new player into the market and its services are subject to high requirements.'
However, given the attitude of mobile operators, the complete indifference of the Czech regulatory authorities is simply astonishing.
It is not just the attitude of the ČTU that is at issue here, which unfortunately has no right to interfere in economic competition in the Czech Republic, unlike the UK and other developed countries.
The Competition Authority shall be the only authority to do so.
But the Bureau has a unique approach to the problem.
'The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would only be possible after a contract for the lease of the necessary infrastructure between the mobile operator and the virtual operator has been concluded.
No such contract has been concluded so far, as the offers of potential interested parties were probably not sufficiently attractive to traditional suppliers', said Kristián Chlapua, external relations officer at the Competition Authority.
A statement from the service providers in this way would probably not surprise anyone.
But from an agency that should represent consumers and, among other things, ensure that no one takes advantage of their market position, this is beyond strange.
In particular, as Kristián Chalupa adds: 'In the overseas countries where virtual service providers are generally active, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to the fall in the price of mobile phone services.'
However, it is likely that the pressure to ensure that the market environment functions properly and to reduce prices is not in the interest of ÚOHS.
In this case, the very touching consistency of the three mobile operators' reactions is indeed shocking.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence is almost self-evident.
Just as gasoline prices at gas stations are identical, they are probably the result of chance and fierce competition.
'The Office has not detected any signs of anti-competitive conduct in this case and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
Neither provider has a leading position, i.e. a proportionately greater responsibility for its market behaviour.
The telecommunications regulator probably lacks the tools to open up the mobile market for virtual operators,' Chalupa said.
The presentation of the market leadership is one of the many points of dispute.
There is of course an analysis of the relevant markets developed by ČTÚ, which shows that telecommunications is the only market from the point of view of economic competition.
In such a market, of course, no Czech service provider is in a leading position.
However, some legal experts offer a different approach - the establishment of a virtual service provider always requires the approval of the network operator.
And the mobile operator has, relatively logically, a monopoly on its own network.
So in a certain segment, it's necessarily dominant.
However, even if this argument were not accepted, the fact that three mobile operators behave in a remarkably similar way should be a minimum warning to the OHIM.
Meanwhile, complaints from a number of interested parties (including GTS Novera, mentioned above) show that they encounter very similar obstacles in negotiations with all providers.
The transfer of responsibility to the CTU is a relatively common trick in telecommunications, which takes the CTU's hand off the whole thing.
We've seen this before in a few similar situations.
Unfortunately, the recently adopted text of the Telecommunications Act did not translate the extension of ČTÚ's competence in the area of economic competition into telecommunications, although many experts hoped that this would improve the situation.
The representatives of the HSE should know this, but they probably have other interests.
It works when no one's watching.
In the meantime, the existence of some virtual operators, many of which are already operating on Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
These are companies that issue their own price lists for mobile phone services, which are however only partially public.
Because they're all multi-level marketing companies.
For example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
The price lists of these companies are usually only available to the chosen few.
The magic is that the company acts as a classic corporate customer to the service provider, ordering a large number of SIM cards.
As a preferred customer, you will then receive special offers (and other discounts).
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such a measure.
'If the cases you are talking about arose, it would be a breach of contract that we would be dealing with and that could lead to the termination of the cooperation with the company in question,' Martina Kemrová answered our question on this problem.
But it is unlikely that news of such activity would have escaped the attention of the operators.
In particular, the three companies mentioned above may have thousands of customers.
Meanwhile, no service provider is immune from such a procedure.
These companies are not negligibly profitable and, unlike the genuine virtual service providers, are not particularly threatened by their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns of potential problems: "The law allows for such speculation, yet only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
They must also accept that the SIM card is not in their name on their phone and therefore cannot be used in full as a general customer of mobile operators.'
But that's what the CTU should be strangest about.
In addition, another question arises for OHIM.
If mobile operators are turning a blind eye to this kind of procedure, why are they preventing the birth of the virtual service provider?
It must be added that the OHIM has a relatively strong power to detect such activity and, if it does not wish to do so, it must not be satisfied with the providers' explanation that they did not foresee such an activity and that their commercial conditions prohibit it.
When we're not the most expensive
As already stated several times in the text, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has led to a significant decrease in the prices of services.
Meanwhile, in virtually all countries where virtual service providers have been established, traditional service providers have tried to prevent their establishment to a greater or lesser extent.
The arguments used were virtually identical - too small, possibly too satisfied market, problems with quality of services, etc.
In developed countries, however, regulators have intervened at precisely these times, in no way protecting the interests of mobile operators but those of their customers.
Then, either through formal measures or informal pressure, they managed to create the first virtual service that others followed.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are mixing the whole thing up.
In our experience, we cannot escape the impression that ambiguous competences are useful in these cases.
But let's not give up the fight.
If the background information is good and the virtual service provider really comes soon, the Czech mobile market may be back on track.
If one operator allows the creation of a virtual mobile operator, the ÚOHS cannot be indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of further interested parties.
And we may not be more expensive to call than the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the Best
Listen to four renditions of the new version of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek presented the new recordings of the national anthem "Where Is My Country?" on the day of the Czech Republic.
The anthem was recorded by the National Theatre Orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
Four versions are available - male or female singers, vocalists or instrumentalists.
The singers are Katerina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
The authors of the hymn's modification are Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček.
All four versions can be heard on the iHNed.cz website.
Bělohlávek considers the Czech national anthem one of the most beautiful hymns.
He has previously told Czech Radio that he has deliberately selected young singers with representative voices who are expressive and popular to sing the solo variations.
"From the beginning, I tried to keep both of them and later the orchestra clear of diction, clear of text, and harmonious", he said.
The Czech national anthem is celebrating its 175th anniversary next year.
The song "Where is my country?" was first performed at the Rendi Theatre in 1834 in Josef Kajetán Tyl Fidlovačka's play, with music by František Škroup.
It became popular and people spontaneously took it as their own.
The first verse of the song became a natural part of the national anthem after Czechoslovakia was formed in 1918.
After the formation of the independent Czech Republic, it remained one of the seven state symbols.
What's the "new" anthem?
Prague's transport company is delivering on a chip card for the first time on Wednesday.
Wednesday, October 1, 2008, will go down in the history of the Prague Transport Company as the date when the first passengers boarding the subway, tram and bus will have an electronic voucher in their pocket instead of a paper ticket.
The voucher is currently available to approximately 100,000 Opencard chip card holders.
Passengers can purchase and at the same time save on their chip cards a 30-day, 90-day and annual coupon (valid from 1 January 2009) at the information centres and offices of the Transport Company at the Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka metro stations.
The tickets can be purchased online from yesterday on the website of the Transport Agency www.dpp.cz.
By this afternoon, more than 400 customers had used the service.
Those who start using online shopping can forget about the ticket offices at subway stations, where they used to regularly stand in long lines for tickets.
The voucher can be purchased online and saved on an Opencard card in one of the 13 branches of the City Library.
"At these places, passengers have a counter with trained servers to help them shop online and save their vouchers on their cards", said Martin Opatrný, spokesman for the project.
In addition to libraries, electronic vouchers will be available for Opencard savings in the self-service machines in some halls.
What do these vending machines look like?
Red, they remind passengers of ticket counters and passengers may have already noticed them at the Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská metro stations.
"Currently there are five of them in the city, but by the end of the year there should be 80", Opatrný added.
The coupon is checked automatically instead of by the driver
The automata, which start operating tomorrow, are easy to operate.
All you have to do is insert the Opencard chip card and the previously paid coupon will be saved by itself.
The electronic coupons will be valid from tomorrow not only in the capital but also in the surrounding areas.
So on the city-wide trains and bus lines 300 to 499, which mainly serve residents of the central Czech roads to the capital.
"On trains in Prague's integrated transport system, the guides were equipped with card readers to check the validity of the tickets", explained ticket checking Filip Drapal of Ropid, the Prague public transport scheduler.
In buses around the city, card readers are installed at the driver's desk.
The driver must therefore not only present the chip card at the time of boarding, but also place the Opencard in a designated place on the side of the ticket office.
It's how the driver checks the validity of the coupons.
"For example, if a passenger needs to check the validity of coupons, the easiest way is to ask the driver", Drápal added.
Passengers who do not use city buses and who will not remember when their voucher expires can again go to the vending machines that save the voucher on their cards.
Information on the validity of their documents will be displayed on the display of the equipment.
The Sudetenlanders wanted a referendum from the United States.
In 1945, the Sudeten Germans asked for Šumava to be annexed by the United States.
This is shown by the letter, which is in the collection of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
If we can't be part of Germany or Austria, at least we want to live under the patronage of the United States of America.
It is said that in 1945 some groups of Sudeten Germans approached the President of the United States with this wish.
This is also shown by a letter that survived from a private archive and is now kept in the collection of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
The Germans in Česky Krumlov are asking the US president not to allow the return of the "Schumava County" to the Czech Republic, which Hitler had seized under the Munich Agreement.
"We have interpreted the situation correctly and we really want to be sure of the words that the American troops are not coming to German territory as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators", the letter reads, signed with the words "Men who carry the fate of Šumava in their hearts".
Since annexation of Czechoslovakia supposedly gives Sudeten Germans - with the knowledge of the Czech national character - only hope for brutality, ruthlessness, lack of understanding, oppression and slavery, the letter's authors ask the American president to take over the protectorate over Šumava "now and forever".
"We cannot believe that, regardless of the opinion of four million inhabitants, this territory would be considered a foreign country to us, oppressing and upsetting the minority, and would do almost nothing to help the Allies win", the letter says.
The reason why the authors could not sign was allegedly fear of revenge from the "Czech oppressors".
So if the president of the United States were supposed to doubt the opinion of the Germans in Schumacher, it would be enough for him to hold a referendum in Schumacher County on whether its residents want to become part of the United States and live under the patronage of the United States.
Although the letter's text may seem a bit naive in light of current knowledge of postwar history, some historians feel that it adequately reflects the expectations of Sudeten Germans at the time.
Even if the Czechs had a slight sense of their expulsion, few of them acknowledged the possibility.
Some expected the United States and Britain to agree to a form of autonomy for the Sudetenland.
Still others hoped to simply remain in Czechoslovakia.
