Two aspects of brain structure make it difficult to transfer our own subjective experiences to animals.
Circuits associated with human consciousness almost always include the lateral prefrontal cortex (due to its role in short-term memory and executive/ management functions).
This wide area is more highly developed in humans than in other primates and seems to be completely absent in other living things.
At least in aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, like our sense of who we are, or our ability to plan and make decisions, it's reasonable to assume that humans are even different from other primates.
Another dramatic feature of the human nature of language is that since a large part of human experience is related to language, consciousness is often said to depend on it.
In this case, animals are excluded.
But even if consciousness were independent of language, it would certainly be affected by language, so animal consciousness, whatever its nature, is probably very different from most of our states of consciousness.
So it's hard to say what consciousness is like in other animals.
If consciousness is not measured as something internal and subjective, and if it cannot be analyzed by our own experience because of special hardware, then his research poses serious problems.
Most of my discussion is about the content of conscious living, but there's another aspect of consciousness that's probably more accessible to science.
The cognitive processes of animals could be studied regardless of their content, and this is exactly what happens in primate short-term memory experiments, especially in the case of visualization.
However, in this hypothesis, also explored by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, they rely more on neural connections of consciousness than on causal mechanisms: Both may or may not be the same.
Interestingly, this hypothesis also highlights the importance of the prefrontal cortex in visualization.
What does this mean about emotions?
I'm guessing it's because an emotional system like fear is activated in the brain when it's aware of its own activity.
So what we call "fear" is the mental state we are in when the activity of a localized defense system in the brain (or its consequences, such as bodily reactions) occupies working memory.
So, emotion is closely linked to areas of the cerebral cortex that are specific to primates and especially to humans.
Along with language, perception is broken down into subtle levels because words and grammar allow us to distinguish and categorize conditions to describe to others, not just ourselves.
In contrast, Antonio Damasio, for example, is of the opinion that emotions come from the simpler activities of the cortex and the brainstem, as does Jaak Pankseep, who, however, focuses more on the brainstem.
Because this network hasn't changed much over human evolution, it could easily play a role in species-wide emotions.
I can't disprove it theoretically, but I think it's unprovable.
Pankseep believes that what seems to be fear in rats and humans is probably also felt in both cases: How could one test whether rats and humans feel the same when they behave similarly?
A cockroach runs away when it's in danger, does it feel fear?
In my opinion, just the same behavior is not proof of the same experience.
Although neural comparisons are helpful: Rats and humans have similar brainstems, but cockroaches do not have brains.
But the brainstem is responsible for emotions?
And even if this could be proven in humans, how could we prove it in rats?
I think rats and other mammals, but maybe even cockroaches, who knows?
However, I don't know how to prove it.
And because their emotions are supposedly fundamentally different from ours (because human consciousness is based on special circuits and language), I'm more interested in the emotional behavior of rats than in their emotional emotions.
But any progress in this area is predictable at the neural level, if we measure the same thing in rats and humans.
And just as I don't research language and consciousness in rats, I don't research emotions because I don't know if they exist.
