Ethiopian Haile Gebrselassie once again showed why he is considered by many to be the greatest middle- and long-distance runner ever when he broke his own world record in Berlin on Sunday, becoming the first man to run the 42.2 kilometers in 2 hours and 4 minutes.
With a comfortable flat track victory in 2:03:59, Gebrselassie improved by 27 seconds on his previous mark of 2:04:26 set last year in Berlin.
By the age of 35, Gebrselassie had set a career-high 26 world records in so many different distances that he had won world championships or set world records at almost every distance, from the 1,500 meters to the marathon.
Last month Gebrselassie missed the Beijing Olympics marathon for fear - in retrospect, perhaps a little too cautious - that air pollution would further aggravate his asthma problems.
Instead, he entered me for the Berlin Marathon.
In near-perfect conditions - sunny, at first 9°C, then 13°C - Gebrselassie won Sunday with an incredible 2 minutes 56 seconds per kilometer.
Since marathoners who had not started before, such as Gebrselassie and Kenyan Paul Tergat, have switched to longer distances, the marathon record has dropped by more than two minutes in the last decade, since Brazil's Ronaldo da Costa won in Berlin in 1998 with a time of 2:06:05.
After Sunday's victory, Gebrselassie told reporters that two weeks ago, he wrinkled both legs and was unable to train for two weeks.
Obviously, he was refreshed during the forced rest and not rusty.
"I'm so pleased", Gebrselassie told reporters.
"Everything worked out perfectly.
A week ago I started training again, and today I had doubts, but in the end everything worked out".
He has received some criticism - particularly from Kenya, Ethiopia's East African rival - for using too many props in his races, usually avoiding many world-famous marathoners, relying on his sprinters as if he were running on a track, and putting world records ahead of the spirit of competition.
However, this criticism hardly diminishes Gebrselassie's greatness in the long jump.
Gebrselassie crossed the finish line Sunday with four Kenyan sprinters in 1:02:04.
