A segregated city, black pride and trials
In the Greater Orlando theme park, a few miles from everything shiny and loud and mighty, lies a quiet little town, where the pride and complexity of the African-American experience was born.
Eatonville, the first all-black city to be integrated into the country, and the childhood home of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as simple as it was in 1935: "Five lakes, three croquet courts, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, plenty of guavas, and two school towns, no jail".
It's a pilgrimage now.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee have all attended the annual Zora Festival, a series of celebrations in Eatonville honoring Hurston, the most famous female writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
Yet, in many ways the city he described and made a tourist attraction - which is also featured in a Florida guidebook published by the Federal Writers' Project of the Depression - is separate from its surroundings.
It is as independent, dignified, and withdrawn as it was in the 1930's, when, as Hurston wrote, Florida's urban blacks were often unwilling to share their true thoughts with white people who "know so little about us that they don't know what they're missing".
Even in a year when black presidential candidate Barack Obama is encouraging open discussion on race, many here are wary of the outsider's gaze.
"We take great care in how our story is told", said 59-year-old Hortense Jones, a lifelong resident of the area and a member of the city's oldest church.
"You have to tell it right".
Eatonville has long been known for its paradox of victory and struggle.
It's both a historic model of black empowerment and a community of nearly 2,400 people with poverty rates twice the national average.
Partly a literary hub, partly an example of the American slave culture, sometimes despised, sometimes praised, Southern, urban, black culture that thrives in the shade of oak trees.
It is not surprising, then, that the people here are both proud and defensive.
And the image of Eatonville has been important since Zora, (that's how everyone here calls Hurston).
In books written in a sincere, strong dialect - such as "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937) - he introduced his hometown to the world.
The five paragraphs of the Florida Roadmap transformed the town, which lies along Route 17, from the long-forgotten center of Florida to one of the sites of black history and human drama.
Hurston, as brave as a drum in life and literature, introduced his readers to the business of Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then to the more intimate spheres.
He wrote: "To the right of the road is the modern public school, with a brown base with a white border, with neatly kept courtyards and playgrounds, which Howard Miller maintains, though he can hardly read or write".
He mentioned the widow Dash's new husband, and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells all kinds of liquor and anything that might be needed in the temporary accommodations".
So in a few hundred words, Hurston linked Eatonville to autonomy, but also to illiteracy, remarriage and sex.
Clearly, Fodor's travel guide said otherwise.
That description really didn't sit well with everyone.
"Zora told things as they were", reported 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of Johnson's daughters, who were immortalized by Hurston's quotes from the slick songs men sang about their beauty.
He added: "Some people didn't like that".
Hurston is still remembered as a lively stranger who visited often after his family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Augustus Franklin, 77, recalled that when Hurston stormed into town, he usually arrived unannounced in a booming Chevrolet, smoking and wearing long pants in a town where people still pride themselves on their dignified dress.
Most people were charmed by it, Franklin said, but many were disillusioned.
"People were always happy to see Zora", Franklin said.
However, on the terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, he rocked his chair and added: "He never stayed too long".
When Hurston died in 1960, he was poor and his books were never published again.
It seemed that Eatonville, along with most of the world, had forgotten about him.
Although she was once a popular writer, a contemporary of Langston Hughes, and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an unmarked grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she had lived before.
There were no major commemorations or large public readings in Eatonville.
"I don't think they understood how much he enriched the world or what he left us", said Valerie Boyd, author of Hurston's 2003 biography, "Wrapped in a Rainbow".
The turning point came in 1980.
Orange County officials wanted to build a five-lane road through the city to replace the two-lane main street, Kennedy Avenue, which played an important role in the life of the community.
The expanding Orlando has already penetrated the Interstate 4 interstate on the city's western border.
The proposal came at a time when Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult historical period.
Forced integration, among other things, has ended the community's relatively idyllic isolation.
In the 1950's, the struggles over racial mixing were tearing the community apart.
"Then a group of white boys came over and threw oranges and other things at people sitting on the side of the road", Franklin said.
"There was a lady who died from this.
They threw a pumpkin out of a car".
In a 1955 letter to The Orlando Sentinel, Hurston questioned the Supreme Court's decision to require forced integration, saying of Brown v. Board of Education that it was "more offensive than respectful of my race".
Today, residents say that while segregation in schools has been positive in some ways, it has weakened the unity of Eatonville and undermined the self-esteem of young people.
"Black children were used to being hugged - I remember - and the teacher was hugged morning and night", reported N. Y. Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins, executive director of Save the Eatonville Community, a nonprofit organization.
"It took as long as the students and teachers were from the same place", he added.
"We didn't hug our white teacher because she was a white teacher - I mean there were cultural differences between us", Nathiri said.
But human rights helped to elevate many other Zora Neale Hurston writers, actors, and artists who rose above prejudice, as she did, with optimistic confidence and lines like, "How can anyone deprive themselves of the pleasure of my company?
It's beyond my comprehension".
In 1975, Alice Walker visited Hurston's unmarked grave and began a fight to restore her reputation.
Five years later, a highly acclaimed biography of Hurston by Robert E. Hemenway appeared on bookshelves, once again elevating him to the top of the American picture book industry.
The road project was to begin just as Eatonville's most famous daughter was once again in the spotlight.
And this time Hurston's old neighbors saw him as a savior.
In 1988, the community started a Hurston festival to show what the county would destroy with the highway.
Thousands of fans came to the opening event two years later, and many have returned to the celebration every January since then.
A few years later, the county withdrew its proposal to build a road.
"The five-lane highway has revived the community, bringing it to full speed, which is a real pride of citizenship", Nathiri said.
Boyd put it more simply: "Zora saved Eatonville".
The victory over the road project helped change the city's image of itself.
More and more out-of-towners, like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who started attending church here in 1993, and the locals began to reevaluate the past.
Eatonville was placed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1998.
In 2006, the new, one-story library (named after Hurston, of course) opened on the newly re-lined and beautified Kennedy Avenue.
Eatonville remains a Florida cockroach's egg: it's only six miles from downtown Orlando, but sometimes you feel like a suburban back street in the summer rainy season; as small as when it was founded by 27 black families in the 1880s.
(Today, 90% of the population is black.)
They still treat outsiders with caution who come here looking for a story to tell about Eatonville.
Most interviews require prior permission, and some things - such as Eatonville's oldest mural, painted by a white man and depicting blacks working the land - are not allowed to be photographed.
Many in Eatonville - including the confident teacher Jones, who is particularly drawn to bright red - fear that their segregated community will be misunderstood.
And yet, as the Hurston Festival grew in popularity, so did the pride of the hometown.
Young people in particular are increasingly seeing Eatonville as Hurston saw his own race: wonderful, with its problems and all, neither better nor worse, as proud, creative, hardworking, foolish and confused as any other racial and ethnic group in America.
Sincere civic engagement is echoed in the words of Franklin's nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, who plans to return after college to take a job with a local government or police department that he believes needs help.
And it seems that even younger people have learned to properly describe Eatonville, like the 11-year-old Winter Park twins Alondra and Alexia Kenon.
"Most people who just pass through here think this town is nothing compared to the rest", said Alondra Kenon recently after church on a Sunday.
"But if you stop and take a moment to learn about its history, it's a very beautiful city".
