"If the plan is really doomed . . . , the Fed and other central banks will have to deal with the crisis and the lending conditions will tighten further", warns Brian Bethune, chief economist at Global Insight.
To add to the sense of urgency, Piegza adds: "Financial institutions are going bankrupt every day" in the United States.
After the collapse of Washington Mutual on Friday, the authorities made sure that Wachovia's banking business was bought by its rival, Citigroup.
The crisis in Europe has accelerated abruptly, necessitating emergency bailouts of banks in the United Kingdom, the Benelux countries, Iceland, and Germany, signaling that the market is "in a crisis not just in the United States but worldwide", adds an FTN Financial analyst.
The bond market has rebounded significantly.
