Blood Safe Again
Héma-Québec celebrated its tenth anniversary yesterday, and President Francine Décary had good reason to celebrate, because Héma-Québec has become one of the safest and most efficient blood donation companies in the world.
Most important, he has managed to regain public confidence, which was severely shaken by the contaminated blood scandal of the 1980's and 1990's.
As you know, the national blood supply managed by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Service was infected with the acquired immunodeficiency syndrome (HIV) and hepatitis C viruses in the 1980s.
Following the tragedy and the general uproar, the Canadian government launched a formal investigation in February 1994, led by Justice Horace Krever, to shed light on the circumstances that led to the tragedy and to formulate recommendations for avoiding similar cases in the future.
While Judge Krever's report was delayed, some provinces set up their own committee to design a new blood system for Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Commission fulfilled this task.
The Gélineau and Krever Reports led to the creation of two blood services in Canada: Héma-Québec, which serves Québec, and the Canadian Blood Services, which serves all other provinces and territories.
"When Héma-Québec began operations in 1998, only 38 percent of people had confidence in the Quebec blood supply system", recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was desperate.
"In the years since, however, we have been able to regain public confidence by improving the safety of blood products and by working in the field". Décary proudly reports that by early 2008, almost 94% of Quebecers had trusted Héma-Québec.
However, Dr. Décary does not forget that "trust is an extremely fragile thing".
Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle since its establishment on 28 September 1998.
During this period, a number of cases of the new strain of the disease, Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, were detected in Europe, infecting humans, says the doctor, who has been running the company since it was founded in 1998.
"We had no idea that this disease was transmitted through blood.
We therefore relied on one of the key recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports, which was that if we are unsure and there is a risk of serious disease, we should take exclusionary measures, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which causes brain damage and inevitably leads to death.
So in April 1999, we did not accept blood from people who had been in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
And a few years ago, it was established beyond a doubt that the disease is also transmitted through blood.
This case convinced us that it made sense to apply the precautionary principle".
In 1999, a technique that allows for a more precise diagnosis of HIV was introduced, the nucleic acid test (NAT), which can directly detect the virus itself in the blood of donors rather than the antibodies produced against the virus, on which previous tests were based.
"The NAT test has shortened the window from infection to detection of the virus in the blood with our technical tools", he explains.
This period could be reduced to less than one week.
This significantly reduced the risk of unknowingly contaminating the blood supply and preventing detection.
These developments have greatly reduced the risk of AIDS being spread by blood transfusion.
The risk of someone getting infected with HIV in blood today is 12 million to one.
"In other words, this means that we would have to distribute 12 million blood products while someone is infected with HIV.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it would take more than 24 years for one such case to occur and for someone to become infected with HIV through a blood product.
"I think that today anyone can freely accept or prescribe a blood transfusion to restore health", says Héma-Québec's number one executive.
"The challenge of the next decade will be to maintain the reliability of our products.
We never know what new pathogen will enter the system.
Just last year, the chikungunya virus appeared on Réunion Island, where it is transmitted through insect bites, similar to the West Nile virus.
Therefore, we must be on the alert at all times", continued Dr Décary, stressing that in addition to emergency reserves, Héma-Québec must provide sufficient permanent reserves.
"As the population ages, so do the needs.
As cancer treatments have become more aggressive, patients often need to replace red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing population also affects the blood supply, as only 3% of the population of Quebec is eligible to donate blood.
However, any healthy person who is at least 18 years of age and who meets the eligibility criteria may donate blood every 56 days, that is, six times a year.
On average, 14 percent of applicants will not accept blood because they have been infected with AIDS or malaria, for example, and those who have been in a country where malaria is rampant are not eligible to donate blood for a year.
"With this 3 percent, we have enough reserves to meet the needs of hospitals.
It's very rare to run out of supplies.
But we have to increase the number of donors as the existing ones get older, because they can't donate blood after a while.
But it is very difficult to convince people to donate blood, but even more difficult to keep them and to get them to become regular blood donors.
In today's fast-paced world, you have barely an hour to go and donate blood". - Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products but also human tissue, such as bone grafts, heart valves, eyeball tissue, and skin tissue, used almost exclusively in cases of severe burns.
These tissues are analysed, transformed and frozen and then placed at Héma-Québec, which also manages Québec's only public stem cell bank.
Once treated as medical waste, cord blood can be harvested to produce blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"We celebrated the arrival of our 1,000th cord blood sample in our bank a few weeks ago, and we plan to take more than 1,000 new samples each year.
We will probably start offering them for transplantation early next year", said Dr. Décary, who says that the cord blood program is very popular today.
"Many mothers are sad that they cannot afford it" - indeed, Héma-Québec is unable to make this complex and expensive programme available in all hospitals in Québec.
