The Orwellian speech of Barrick Gold
In the September 17 issue of Le Devoir, there was a letter from Patrick J. Garver, deputy president and CEO of Barrick Gold in Canada.
In response to Orwell's argument, Garver states that the world's largest gold mining company has filed a six million dollar libel suit against three authors and a small-cap publishing company to initiate what he calls a "public debate".
Although the judges are independent and impartial, their decisions - especially in defamation cases - are based, not on truth, but on law.
It's no surprise that Garver was deeply silent about this fundamental difference.
Is it really the best way for Barrick Gold to have a public debate to destroy anyone who disagrees with their position?
Regardless of the outcome of the case, the authors and publishers of Noir Canada must spend considerable sums of money to defend and fight an unequal battle with an army of lawyers on the other side, supported by the almost inexhaustible resources of the mining industry.
In such an unequal fight, tactics often include subverting the defendant and striking a friendly agreement, not only to silence the opposing side but also to intimidate those who try to reopen the matter.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, they should have put their views out there.
Although this is different in many other countries where Barrick Gold operates, in Canada the parties to the dispute generally do not hit each other with sticks but express their thoughts.
The mine would have simply opened its books and files and prepared for a real debate in the press, in the media, in publications, paying independent research groups to shed light on the issue.
But it seems that Barrick Gold doesn't trust the public and in one move, it's sweeping away petitions and letters written in defense of the authors of Noir Canada.
Mr. Garver, perhaps you could explain how you can initiate a "public" debate if you ignore the opinion of this public?
In the vice president's mind, the word probably refers only to the badly paid lawyers, not to the entire population of Canada.
In a democratic state, even those who insult others have the right to free speech.
Barrick Gold, on the other hand, does not understand - or does not want to understand - that the main reason why the public supports the authors and publishers of Noir Canada is because they condemn the mining company's harsh practices.
The public is willing to hear Barrick and pass judgment, but they would do so on the basis of civilized reasoning, rather than a lawsuit that many would rather have silenced. (Incidentally, Barrick Gold recently wrote to the authors of Noir Canada to refrain from using the term.)
In addition to Garver's surreal arguments, the Barrick Gold trial is an open attack on the freedom of academic research and the pursuit of truth, which are the building blocks of every democratic society.
The whole procedure denies the right to cite credible sources, to debate facts and their interpretation, which are the basis of intellectual activity.
If a country like Canada can study and discuss subjects that are not appealing to the wealthy corporations of today's world, who will have the courage to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wants an open and transparent debate, it should do so according to the scientific standards that the authors of Noir Canada apply.
You have the right to answer.
In our academic circle, we've been able to handle arguments, disagreements and conflicts for a long time.
Barrick Gold's reckless behavior clearly shows that contrary to what it claims, it has no desire to engage in open debate.
This is a loss for both the academic world and the Canadian public debate institution, and it is time for governments to finally put in place measures that limit legal proceedings for such abuse.
The Wall Street bailout is a deal between Democrats and Republicans.
The Bush administration and congressional leaders, Republican and Democratic, finally reached an agreement yesterday on an economic bailout, the largest such plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The $700 billion plan to stem the financial crisis that has plagued Wall Street for months has yet to be approved by both houses of Congress.
The main points of the plan are: more effective monitoring of implementation by the representatives; new mechanisms to ensure the reimbursement of public funds allocated; new provisions to keep the number of houses occupied due to late payment at a level; access to the salaries of managers of companies receiving aid.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, House Speaker Nancy Pelosi and Judd Gregg, the Republican congressman who was in the hearing yesterday, announced the good news just minutes before midnight after a two-day marathon hearing.
"We have made great progress toward a solution that will work effectively in markets", declared Henry Paulson, a representative of the Bush administration.
"Everything we did was to save the real economy and the American people from the current crisis on Wall Street", the Democrat explained.
"The most important aspect is that if we don't do this, there will be a huge shock, chaos and disruption in the daily lives of Americans", said Rep. Judd Gregg, R-N.C.
The hearing has been accelerated in the last few hours over fears that another failure could have a detrimental impact on investor sentiment.
They gave you a deadline to make a deal until the stock market opens this morning.
Two presidential candidates who joined the negotiations late showed willingness to reach an agreement, but expressed displeasure that the situation had escalated to extremes.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama has credited himself with expanding the agreement with provisions such as the retention of homeownership or the pay of state-assisted corporate executives.
"When we ask the taxpayer to take some extraordinary steps because of the irresponsibility of other people, it is not a very welcome thing.
But these steps are necessary", he noted on a U.S. television program.
When asked by another network if he would vote for the proposed plan, he replied, "I'd like to know the details, but I hope so".
"From what I have read in broad outline, it is clear that this is something that we all have to digest and move on from.
The possibility of doing nothing is simply unacceptable", he said.
The $700 billion plan would use taxpayer money to buy the dubious claims of American financial institutions, their somewhat risky, unsellable assets.
The plan was preceded by a 14-month crisis triggered by the bursting of the housing bubble, which first led to the collapse of subprime mortgages, then spread to other debt-backed (commercial) securities, and finally led to the freezing of liquidity and the insolvency of banks and financial institutions.
The first draft of the agreement was defeated by a group of Republican representatives last week.
It seems we've gotten out of this dead end since the Democrats agreed to let the government provide certain "toxic" assets to struggling companies rather than buy them.
To satisfy all members of Congress, the plan included a provision that if the government had to bear losses under the program for five years, it could impose new taxes to recover its resources.
As part of the new plan, a $250 billion installment would be paid first, followed by another $100 billion if the president sees fit.
The remaining $350 billion would have to be approved by Congress in another vote.
In return for the aid, Washington will acquire shares in the companies it helps, which will give it a dividend on the profits, which it can sell after the crisis has passed.
The Federal Government will be able to delay the seizure of the property used as collateral for the mortgage loans covered by the plan and to set the maximum amount of salary and severance pay for the managers of the companies affected by the crisis.
The plan's developers want the House to vote on it today and the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite their efforts, however, it is still uncertain whether the plan will be approved.
Because there were repeated statements against the plan yesterday from both Republicans and Democrats.
"It is clear that Washington does not hear your voice", Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House Finance Committee, told his constituents.
"Yes, we have serious financial problems.
Yes, there are solutions.
But none that would benefit the taxpayers".
Brad Sherman, the Democratic congressman who leads a small congressional group called the "skeptic faction", presents things differently, but he comes to the same conclusion.
"Four hundred leading economists, including three Nobel laureates, have written to us asking Congress to take its time and consider carefully which path to take", Sherman said yesterday.
Europe, at the same moment, understood once again that this was a global crisis.
Following a crisis conference, the three Benelux countries announced that they were going to nationalise a part of the Fortis banking group worth EUR 11,2 billion (USD 16,3 billion).
The intervention of the Belgian, Dutch and Luxembourg governments was necessary after the French BNP Paribas announced that it would not acquire its bankrupt competitor after losing EUR 2 million (USD 2,9 billion) in the secondary mortgage crisis in the United States.
Fortis, with 85,000 employees, is one of the 20 largest European banks and one of the 10 largest insurance companies.
"This is not money wasted", Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said yesterday.
"In return, we get voting rights and influence at the bank.
This is precisely what depositors and households value now that the situation is looking uncertain".
Meanwhile, across the English Channel, the British government appears to be preparing to nationalize another bank that has been squeezed by the financial crisis.
According to the British press, the government would take over all of the outstanding loans of Bradford and Bringley Bank, of which the real estate loans amount to £41 billion (US$75.5 billion).
The Spanish bank Santander announced yesterday that it will acquire the British bank's subsidiaries and client base.
Bradford and Bringley would thus be the second bank to be nationalised by the UK Government since the start of the crisis, after Northern Rock.
