The psychology of over-bidding: Why spend more money?
At auctions, buyers tend to spend more money, overvalue the goods.
The neuroeconomic basis for this well-known - and seemingly irrational - behavior has been uncovered by researchers at New York University's School of Neuroscience and Economics.
According to their study published in the journal Science, people do not want to be left behind in a type of competition, such as an eBay auction, so they are more likely to pay too high a price.
The research attempted to map out the neural patterns of this "game" using experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played the lottery, the other participated in a player auction, and the subjects' active brain areas were examined by functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI).
Both games offered winners money, but in the auction game, where the key element is to outbid the other party, a complex called the striatum, located under the cerebral cortex, becomes activated when the game is lost.
This area of the brain plays a role in the nervous system's "self-reward" mechanism, among other functions.
The researchers therefore believe that the price increase is due to the avoidance of a severe striatum reaction.
To support their theory, the economists in the research team also conducted a financial follow-up study.
In this case, three groups bid against a partner under different circumstances.
The control group was simply told what the real value of the product was and they took their bets.
Another group was also promised an additional $15 in prize money if they won the game.
The third group received $15 just before the auction, but the other group lost that money if they lost the auction.
The only difference between the two groups was that one group was emphasized for winning and the other group for losing.
However, proving the neurologists' hypothesis, the members of the "losing" team were willing to bet higher than the control and "winning" groups.
"These results cannot be derived from any previously existing economic theory.
They have hitherto only explained the phenomena of the auction by the joy of winning and the avoidance of risk.
Only neurological imaging techniques have helped to resolve the contradiction between these two theories, and now we have a third explanation", notes Andrew Schotter, a professor at New York University's Graduate School of Business.
Hepatitis: When should you see a doctor?
Worldwide, about half a billion people are infected with chronic hepatitis B or C, and chronic liver disease is listed as a leading cause of death in Hungary.
There are 100,000 people in your country with hepatitis, but only 7,000 are being treated, and that's because patients often don't know they're infected.
Hepatitis is a collective term for infectious liver disease caused by various viruses.
They have many similar symptoms, including hepatitis and jaundice, but their pathogens and diseases are different.
Depending on the pathogen, hepatitis viruses are spread in two main ways: hepatitis A and E through the food chain (e.g. through contaminated food, water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses through blood and body fluids (venom, vaginal discharge, saliva).
Travellers should be given a vaccine against A and B viruses, there is no vaccine for C.
Hepatitis A symptoms occur two to three weeks after eating infected food, usually accompanied by malaise, weakness, stomach upset, and nausea.
These can cause yellowing of the skin and eye, light stools, dark urine, and may take two to three weeks to heal.
A million people die each year worldwide from the more serious form of the disease, hepatitis B-related liver cancer and cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that only about one in ten infected people receive medication.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if left untreated, it can lead to cirrhosis of the liver, even liver cancer.
Most people infected are unaware of their disease because the pathogen is secretly destroying liver cells, and in many cases the first symptoms do not appear until 20 or 30 years later.
So then it's very important to do early prevention, to do regular screening.
Three groups have higher rates of this disease than average: people who received blood transfusions before 1991, drug users, and tattoo users.
Worldwide, the number of people currently infected with the chronic hepatitis C virus is estimated at 200 million.
Since the disease can be detected by routine laboratory tests, it is wise to consult a doctor if you notice any symptoms of unknown origin.
Early detection can cure the disease, eliminate the virus from the body, and prevent infection and cancer.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, first observed in 2004 by organizations representing patients around the world.
It aims to raise awareness of viral hepatitis, its causes and the importance of early detection.
Does it hurt less to believe in God?
A recent study found that religious faith acts as a pain reliever that may have helped Catholic martyrs to die.
Scientists at Oxford University conducted an interesting experiment to examine how belief in God affects people's perception of pain, reports the British Telegraph.
In a rather bizarre study, 12 Catholics and an equal number of atheists were given electric shocks while they were all studying a painting of the Virgin Mary.
The results showed that Catholics were able to eliminate most of the pain.
Thanks to the human brain scanning technique, it was also found that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain that is responsible for pain regulation.
The study is the first in a series of studies involving academics as well as scientists, philosophers and theologians from across the university.
The test was done exactly by attaching a spark plug to the left hand of the subject, which provided the electroshock.
The researchers asked the participants to look intently at two paintings, the Virgin Mary by Sassoferrato in the 17th century and the Madonna and Hermes by Leonardo da Vinci in the 15th century.
The researchers hoped that the Virgin Mary's appearance would create a religious mood among the faithful, while the da Vinci image was chosen because it was not too different from the others and was thought to be soothing.
The subjects spent 30 minutes in an MRI scanner, during which time they received 20 electroshocks in four successive sessions, while looking at either the religious theme or the general picture.
Catholics reported feeling "safe" during the visit of the Virgin Mary, as being "cared for" and "calmed down, filled with peace".
They reported 12 percent less pain when viewing the religious painting than when viewing Leonardo's work.
Miguel Farias, a psychologist who was involved in the study, believes that a similar effect can be achieved with any powerful image, even with atheists, if you just find the right one.
"We should find an image that they feel very positive about, like a mother or a father", the psychologist said.
Tom Wright, the Anglican bishop, welcomed the results of the research.
"The practice of faith should and in many cases does change our personality", Wright added.
After the great results, the only question is, if Leonardo or a painter of similar caliber were to show a picture of the Madonna to the faithful, what effect would it have on their pain management?
Would a quality Virgin Mary visit have even better results?
You are what you share about yourself.
On its tenth birthday, Google can tell you that people have at least as much in their pockets as they have in the sky above their heads; it knows where they've been on vacation, what kind of jobs they've been on, what they're interested in.
And that's still not enough, according to Eric Schmidt, one of the company's key people.
But as for the skeptics who draw parallels with Orwellian nightmares, they're missing the essence of Web 2.0.
Eric Schmidt recently told the Financial Times that Google's main goal is to collect more personal data about its users, which is necessary to keep up with the original goal of the founders of Google, which was to "get all the information in the world".
The Google CEO said that after 10 years of disruptive work, the company is still at the beginning of being able to handle all the information.
When asked what will happen in five years, Schmidt said he would like Google to be able to answer questions like "What should I be doing tomorrow?" or "What kind of job would I really be doing?" - but until then, software can't answer these seemingly simple questions because it doesn't know enough about users.
Not all Internet users are aware that search terms are recorded precisely, from which IP address they were searched and to which page they were sent after the search.
Personalized Search, which was launched two years ago, will allow users to store their own browsing history, look back at what they've searched for, what they've clicked on, and in the long run, generate more personalized results for them - the same logic that will be used in Recommendations, which is how the system recommends products and services to us based on our previously stated and recorded preferences.
What if they use my data against me, if they look at what I do?
In most cases, it is the extent of the potential power that the company represents that is scary, not guilt, fear of punishment, desire for freedom, or even rebellion against power that triggers the backlash among netizens.
However, it is a fact that all search terms are not only recorded but can also be passed on to third parties if justified, and nothing protects the privacy rights of internet users in such legal cases.
Perhaps the most prominent example of this in recent times was the coordinated campaign against pedophiles in Brazil, in which Google provided the Brazilian government with identifiable information about pedophiles from the social networking site it maintains called Orkut.
However, privacy-conscious netizens were able to appeal in May when the company, along with the electronic rights organization EFF, successfully argued in court against the FBI that Google could no longer be forced by any provision of the Constitution to secretly serve any information requested by the FBI.
(At the same time, the federal government successfully fought off some 50,000 web addresses and 1,000 search terms, which it had won by invoking the strengthening of the Child Protection Act passed years earlier, but failed to obtain individual user search lists or a complete two-month list of websites and keywords.)
So Google's view is quite controversial: it's being whipped by people who are afraid to give their personal information because they feel their privacy and privacy is being violated by using Google services and are rebelling against the conservative-looking corporations.
Meanwhile, the American geek culture and its drive to bring together enthusiastic computer fans, activists, users in many countries sees them as the next generation of big companies, the "cool corporation", as opposed to their rival, Microsoft, which is poised to conquer the world with Windows, even though they are both fighting for the same goal.
This may be because, unlike Microsoft, Google does not ask users for an identification code, does not charge for its applications, and the open, free, continuously updated source code and software package is much more accessible, younger, cooler than the practice of the official software giant.
But it could also be because geeks are so keenly aware of the problematic relationship between privacy rights and the Internet, which has been one of the most talked about keywords of recent years, Web 2.0.
Because Web 2.0 is all about collaboration, about intentionally leaving a trail and using the channels of communication that we have at our disposal, and while the scale of those varies from person to person, the essence is the same: we show ourselves.
The average teenager can maintain a profile on multiple social networks, from Facebook to Xangai, link to other services like Twitter or last.fm, which lists their music habits, link them to tracking systems like FriendFeed or Blip.fm, and blog automatically with their latest photos from Flickr or Pica.
While there are many examples of this to be seen, the girlfriend easily discovers who her cheating boyfriend spent the evening with by seeing a morning stream of photos from their mutual friendship, or fires a company employee simply because he writes his honest opinion on top management in his blog, a definite notion of privacy has been completely re-evaluated.
The online life is what you show, and that's the basic principle behind the behavior of today's youth.
And anyone who wants to hide something, or at least avoid Google's monopoly, can do so (starting with Scroogle, which uses Google's search engine but also intentionally leaves no trace).
For example, many people will not register for social networking sites on purpose to avoid being found, and Google's online apps, from text editor to image manager to news reader, can be replaced with alternatives that are not tied to huge server fleets and that don't build the best profile of you ever.
The public is not so much waiting in secret for Google to show off their tooth whites.
With a current valuation of $156 billion, more than IBM ($140 billion), Intel ($124 billion) or Coca-Cola ($110 billion), AdWords/AdSense advertising interfaces threaten advertising agency revenues, and the rapidly accelerating introduction of services is a major headache not only for Microsoft but for many other software developers.
Critical observers find these to be disconcertingly contradictory: for example, top management completely rejected employees' objections after doubling the company's nursery fees, management found it too expensive to feed employees multiple meals a day, but all this is dwarfed by the fact that Google submitted to the Chinese government in 2006 and, under their agreement, the company filters out any hits that violate good taste or the interests of the Chinese regime.
One of the company's internal policies is that they don't pre-announce a new service until it's ready to go, but it's clear that the problems that are coming in the coming months and years could move the world to another point: while some people think that Google's book and magazine scanning and archiving project has grown to the point where the company will soon be facing the U.S. Supreme Court, others are terrified of the health system, where we can build a complete health profile of ourselves with our previous findings, our doctors and our problems.
And the fact that Google is building a genetic database could also be a good starting point for the next generation of science fiction writers, as Cory Doctorow's popular novel, Scroogled, describes in Orwellian tones a future in which a human being can only be approached with alarmingly good Google data.
