The intelligent car mimics the flight of the dongo
What better way to develop technologies to avoid collisions than by mimicking the obstacle sensors found in nature?
Like the bees.
In a surprising project presented at CEATEC in Japan, the dongos gave Nissan engineers a strategic starting point for how to build the next generation of collision avoidance systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the BR23C bioreliable robotic steering system, a robotic mini-car endowed with bee characteristics, with the ultimate goal of helping to create a system that eliminates all collisions.
During flight, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space, which is actually very similar to our safety cover", explained Kazuhhiro Doi, technology PR and research and development brand manager at the exhibition.
It is important for the bee's complex eye, which can see in all directions at more than 300 degrees.
To mimic the complex eye's function, engineers have taken up the idea of a laser rangefinder.
This, in a 180-degree field of view in front of BR23C, identifies obstacles within 2 meters, calculates their distance, and sends a signal to the onboard microprocessor, which immediately converts to collision avoidance.
Within a fraction of a second, the obstruction is detected, and the robot mimics the bee's movements and immediately changes direction by turning its wheels to avoid a collision.
Unlike any current system, this evasive maneuver is completely instinctive.
"If it weren't, the car robot wouldn't be able to react fast enough to avoid obstacles", explains Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the car robot project.
It must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and innermost layer of the safety shields, a layer within which collisions are currently considered unavoidable.
The whole process has to mirror what one bee is doing to avoid other bees.
This process must be completed in the blink of an eye.
But unlike bees, the deviation cannot be upward, downward or transversely, it can only be two-dimensional, and only in the direction of the rotation of the wheels.
So instead of the endless possibilities for bees to avoid other bees, here, only rotational motion and acceleration and deceleration were used as the options available to the car robot.
BR23C uses lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and have a higher energy density, which means they have a longer life than the lithium-ion version.
Andoh says that the instinctive intelligent response is important, not the ability to process data, much less store it.
This device only needs to process and respond to a few incoming signals per second.
It doesn't need to store them and responds with intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, so it only uses a few dozen kilobytes of memory at a time.
You don't need gigabytes or megabytes of memory.
This is the first step towards developing the instantaneous avoidance technology that Nissan estimates could be incorporated into mass-produced cars within ten years.
A further application could be to integrate the unit with the GPS satellite navigation system to guide the driver to the given destination by avoiding obstacles on the road.
