The program, by the way, differs from the original proposal of the Bush administration, which was to spend $700 billion on buying low-quality, credit-deficient securities one at a time.
Now, in the first round, up to half of the $700 billion can be spent by using $250 billion immediately after Congress votes on the bill, which is expected to be on Monday, from which the Treasury buys bad credit-backed, bad-rated securities, with the fate of another $100 billion at the discretion of the president.
The program will be overseen by a special committee, including the chairman of the Federal Reserve.
The other half of the $700 billion is up to Congress.
The law allows the Ministry of Finance to use a combination of tactics: to buy bad loans, mortgages and mortgage-backed securities, and other types of 'toxic' loans simultaneously.
