The legislation allows the companies concerned to participate in an insurance scheme where the financial institution guarantees the assets of concern, for which the companies will pay a premium corresponding to the expected losses.
Henry Paulson said the bill would provide the necessary tools to provide up to $700 billion to address the urgent needs of the U.S. financial system, whether it be the widespread purchase and insurance of bad assets or the avoidance of systemic risk from the collapse of a major financial institution.
We will take the necessary steps to be ready to implement the law as soon as it is signed, he added.
But the heads of troubled banks waiting for state bailouts can expect their exit funds - simply called a golden parachute in overseas slang - to be limited by the government.
