The Elite at Risk
The phenomenon was already felt a few days ago when the House of Representatives did not vote on the $700 billion bailout package put forward by the White House: a significant portion of Americans were more interested, and still are, in punishing Wall Street than in saving the economy.
This is confirmed by yesterday's New York Times report that the current crisis has created a rift within the Republican Party, which is showing a growing divide between the traditional, restrained, pro-federal institutions and business-friendly East Coast attitude and the new anti-globalist Washington and financial stance that is gaining momentum in the Midwest and South.
This approach was critically expressed in the House vote mentioned in the introduction.
But this is just one of the many major changes that the economic transformation that is still under way is foreshadowing, or making visible, not only in the United States but throughout the Western world and perhaps beyond.
It seems that the crisis, both in the US and in Europe, is only accelerating the long-standing phenomena that are taking root in this new atmosphere and finally coming to light.
The first of these is the re-actualization, the re-introduction of the dual category of state sovereignty into the public consciousness, in connection with a kind of re-nationalization of the economy.
The crisis affects banking and financial institutions, which, although closely linked to the outside world, mainly and on a fairly large scale, involve people and families living in one country, one state.
This, however, poses a direct political difficulty for those in power: how to respond to the difficulties and protests of people who are also voters.
So while the crisis may seem global in economic terms, it is almost exclusively national in political terms.
Political internationalism seems to be essentially stranded: the European Union, caught between different interests and divergent national strategies, is a prime example of this.
So everyone is waiting for the individual national governments to intervene, to rescue, to revive and to set new rules, but above all to open up the monetary funds: because in a crisis situation, only individual states have the economic resources, the financial reserves, that can be able to fix things.
They have the means and the authority to use them: under the circumstances, they have two invaluable resources that no other market and no international organisation will likely ever have to this extent.
The new emphasis on nation-states given by the crisis is also in line with the fact that recent economic growth has given increasing importance to a factor closely linked to this element: territorial integrity.
And paradoxically, while we were convinced that we had entered the abstract world of the network, of increasingly sophisticated technology, and we were convinced that the global financial world was destined to rule the world, we suddenly realized that our future was increasingly dependent on things that were not at all abstract, like water, crops and oil.
Things that can be transported from one end of the planet to the other, but are still completely confined to a confined space, a confined area.
So, a person who dominates the territory has a lot more cards than someone who was unfortunately born in a place where there are no crops, no oil and no water.
I would like to move on to the second innovation, which suggests a kind of fault line.
When you say territory, state, government, you're necessarily saying politics, or leadership.
In this respect, the economic crisis seems to produce two overlapping phenomena:
One is the objective recognition that we need credible leadership, someone who can take charge of events.
On the other hand, it brings complete discredit to the current leadership, especially the business leaders, who have proven themselves totally incompetent and have shown that there is still a lot of uncertain territory ahead.
The two together have a deeper meaning and in some ways are even more disturbing: the sense of disbelief, impatience, incompetence and isolation that increasingly affects the entire leadership elite in more and more Western countries.
So it seems that there is a growing belief among the population that the time of the social elite, which was at the top, is over, that it is over before they have made their actions, their experiences, their lifestyles, their culture, in the complex sense of the word, theirs, and that the social elite is becoming more and more alienated from the majority opinion.
In short, the need for leadership, in its veiled form, is fueling a broad but powerful delegitimization movement against the ruling class and the traditional political system, manifested in unexpected "riots" among voters or in recent sudden changes in public sentiment, such as the rise of conservatives to power in Austria and Bavaria, the collapse of the workers' party unity in Britain, or the rebellion of US Congressmen against Bush (and perhaps the victory of the Italian right).
It seems that the traditional elite, with their parties, their programs, and, you might say, their habits, their press, and their prestigious intellectuals, are becoming less and less aware of, and therefore less and less able to represent, what has been going on for some time in the deeper layers of Western society.
Yet, to speak frankly of "the impending revolt of the masses" would be an exaggeration.
