No medication with juice.
You have to be careful with grapefruit, oranges and apples.
These high-vitamin thirst drinks, which are popular especially in summer, when taken with certain life-saving medicines alter their absorption, increasing or decreasing their effect, as appropriate, and can have serious health consequences.
David Bailey, a professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, warned of the dangers of using canned or fresh fruit juices with certain medications when he announced at the 236th National Meeting of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia that a glass of grapefruit, orange, or apple juice can reduce the absorption of certain lifesaving drugs, thus preventing their beneficial effects and endangering the health of the patient.
Grapefruit juice has been on the defense before when it was found to enhance the effects of some antibiotics, antihistamines, anxiolytics, pacemakers, and neurotransmitters to levels considered toxic.
COXICAN DRUGS - Two years ago, the Italian Institute of Pharmacy itself published the news in its official journal, warning doctors and patients to take seriously the risks of the combination and to watch what they drink when taking drugs such as Diazepam or Methadone.
NO GRAPEFRUIT - Researchers say that orange and apple juice also contain substances that interfere with the effectiveness of medications.
The list of active substances that grapefruit and other fruit juices inhibit in the body could be long.
Michele Carruba, professor of pharmacology at the State University of Milan, points out: "Discovery of this kind is usually immediately reported to the various national and international pharmaceutical institutes, which, if necessary, make sure that the information on the package insert of the drug is changed.
Therefore, you should always read the package leaflet of the medicine you are going to buy and if you do not understand something, do not let yourself be influenced, but ask your doctor or pharmacist clearly", stressed the expert from the Ansa Institute.
