Open Office, the third edition of the "anti-Microsoft" package
Today, we're launching OpenOffice.org 3.0, an open source suite of personal productivity applications that is a free alternative to Microsoft Office for a broader audience, from home users to office users, from freelancers to government.
After almost a year of work by volunteer developers and supervised by SUN Microsystem, the new Open Office brings several new features to the public: a welcome screen and a redesigned, less Spartan user interface, as well as several major new features, such as compatibility with the Apple Mac OS X operating system and support for the new ISO-standard ODF (Open Document Format) 1.2.
A special focus was placed on compatibility with Office 2007 so that Open Office can open new Microsoft documents (.docx, .xlsx, .pptx).
There are also some module-specific features, such as the ability to reduce the size of PowerPoint presentations, which can be useful when sending files via email, and support for importing PDFs into a graphics module while maintaining the page layout.
On this same interface, you can create "hybrid PDF" documents, which combine the typical Adobe format with spreadsheet or word processor elements.
In-app sharing has also undergone a number of improvements: the spreadsheet manager supports sharing workbooks but prevents overwriting of each other's work.
Some companies are already working on making some of the features of OpenOffice available on the Internet (on the cloud), so the final version will probably be released in the coming weeks.
The Italian version, which has been available since Friday alongside the English version, can be downloaded from: http://it.openoffice.org/download/3.0.0/download300.html
The software package is available for Linux in addition to the usual Windows and Mac OS operating systems.
On request, you can pick up the installation CD at your home or workplace.
Free is probably the biggest attraction for home application adoption, but the Open Office suite is now trying to hit the business sector with a number of government and school projects.
There is no shortage of ideal training, consultancy and service services for small and medium-sized enterprises, which can open up new business opportunities.
Open Office consists of five basic modules: Writer, a Word-like text editor; Calc, a spreadsheet manager designed to replace Excel; Impress, for PowerPoint-like presentations; Dbase, the most popular, similar to the Access database manager; and finally Draw, the graphics module.
The goal is to reach 5 million downloads in 2008, but considering that we are already at 3.6 million by the time the new version is released, this number is likely to be higher than expected.
