Students suffer from high rents, which can reach up to 900 euros a room
The housing market for university students is not affected by the crisis.
According to a recent survey by the Sunia, the Association of Homeowners, a student can pay up to 900 euros for a one-bedroom in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples and 600 in Rome.
"The phenomenon has now reached such staggering proportions that, because of the huge costs to families, it is preventing a wide range of students from learning", explains Laura Mariani, head of the Sunia study office. "The high demand for students in these cities has distorted the market to such an extent that a general price increase has been introduced against the local population".
In most cases, real estate offers also contain a number of irregularities: unregistered contracts without rent limits, with linked rentals.
According to Sunia, an exceptional measure would be needed to maximise prices by reviewing the tax system.
The survey shows that in the Brianza area of Milan, bed prices are as high as EUR 450 per bed; the average price of a single room ranges from EUR 650 (Bande Nere area) to EUR 800 (Lambiate, Udine and Fiera area) but can reach EUR 900 (Vittoria area).
In Florence, a bed costs on average 350-400 euros, a room about 700.
In Bologna, where most students live in the vicinity of the university, a bed costs 250/280 euros for a double room and 370-500 euros for a single room.
In Rome, in areas close to central universities (San Lorenzo, Piazza Bologna), a bed for a single room costs about 600 euros and a double room about 450 euros.
Prices are somewhat cheaper (€550 a single room) in the other university areas (Ostiense and Cinecittà).
In suburban areas, you can save a little: a bed costs 300 euros and a single room 450 euros in Prenestina, Centocelle and other similar areas.
In Naples, beds are 300/450 euros, rooms 400-600 euros, and the price gap is highest in the area of Policlinico, Vomero and Colli Aminei.
In Bari, you pay 250-350 euros for a bed and at least 350 euros for a single room.
In smaller cities, prices are lower in absolute terms but they have a greater impact on the city budget.
