Goodbye, old Cinema Paradiso, the cities have sacrificed the age of the old cinemas
The traditional cinemas are closing in favour of the multiplexes.
"A city without cinemas is a blind city, like a face without eyes".
The images, made by director Giuseppe Tornatore, are a powerful representation of what is happening in the Italian cities and rural regions.
The displacement of cinemas - the emergence of large multi-screen cinemas in the suburbs and the consequent decline of single-screen cinemas in the city centres - is a process which seems inevitable and irreversible, but which at the same time carries with it all the characteristics of a genuine cultural crime.
When places full of history and memories disappear, "it is as if a friend has left, a friend with whom we shared our journey and many experiences", says the director of Cinema Paradiso.
The figures published by Anec, the largest association of operators, speak for themselves: 316 traditional cinemas have closed in the last five years. e biggest losses were recorded in cinemas in major cities: 10 cinemas closed in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
The most affected regions are Emilia-Romagna, which lost 82 single-screen cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
And the fact that multiplex expansion is responsible for their disappearance is best demonstrated by the fact that these three regions of Italy have the highest number of new multi-screen cinemas: in the last five years, the number of cinemas has increased by 195 in Lombardy, by 81 in Tuscany and by the same amount in Emilia-Romagna.
"The number of cinemas in Italy has increased irrationally", says Paolo Protti, president of Anec. "It is fine to build new facilities, but the survival of the existing ones must also be ensured, because when a city cinema closes, not all the visitors are willing to move to multiplexes.
Not to mention the unused financial resources to support operators: the State's outstanding debt is estimated at around EUR 10 million.
It is a shame, both ethically and morally, that the government does not respect the laws in force.
The market would require EUR 16-18 million a year to be maintained.'
The case of Bologna is particularly noteworthy: it is the first Italian city to have decided, in the face of the closures, to remedy the problem by means of an agreement between the municipality and Anec, in order to protect and promote single-screen cinemas in the outskirts and in the city centre.
The provisions would include tax advantages for operators and benefits for the public to promote accessibility: spectators can enter restricted areas and park at a reduced rate in certain car parks.
'I like this initiative,' says Giuseppe Tornatore, 'and I hope that other cities will follow Bologna's example, perhaps by introducing other measures.
But it's also clear that traditional theaters, in order to be able to fight the dominance of multiplexes, need to improve the quality of sound and picture, because today's audiences are much more demanding.
Preserving traditional cinema has always been an important issue for me: the closure of the Supercinema in Bagheri, where I spent my childhood and youth, gave me the spark that eventually led me to make Cinema Paradiso, even though I had been thinking about it for 10 years.
I've lived in Rome for 25 years, so when I go out on the Via Nazionale in front of the closed Rialto or the Quirinale, to avoid seeing the dust-blackened posters, I turn my head away.
