The energy comes from the waves, and now the big ones are coming.
An inexhaustible source of energy that covers 70 percent of the planet's surface and is only now being discovered by the major international energy companies
Waves, ocean currents, tides, all renewable energy that giants like Chevron have their eye on, and now they're trying to get their hands on.
For a hundred years, people have been exploring the possibility of how to harness energy from the movement of the ocean, and in the 1970s, during the first oil crisis, the search intensified.
Around 1980, when oil prices fell, the idea of exploiting offshore energy was abandoned, but today environmental demands and the resurgence of oil prices are giving the sector a new impetus.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimated in 2007 that 15 percent of the world's electricity needs could be met by offshore wind farms.
This is twice the amount produced by nuclear power plants today.
And then there would be the currents and the tides.
The Giants are in the air.
Enersis was the first company to commit to marine energy and signed an agreement in 2005 for a power plant to be built in northern Portugal.
It seemed like a revolutionary move when the signing was announced.
Two years have passed since then, and more and more companies are turning to offshore power, including those who have been committed supporters of conventional energy.
"Chevron is studying ocean energy technologies and is considering working with us", a spokesman for an affiliate of the U.S. oil giant told the Wall Street Journal business daily.
The cooperation in question concerns the granting of a permit issued by the US Energy Commission for the launch of a marine energy project in Alaska.
This is not insignificant, especially when you consider that the United States is currently drilling for oil in Alaska, and President Bush has recently launched a plan to drill further.
In addition to Chevron, Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey are also pursuing offshore energy, and the amounts invested so far, as far as the details are known, are evidence of growing interest.
The technology is waiting to be developed.
Experts say that this is still a rudimentary technology, not least because energy from the sea does not dispel doubts about its environmental impact.
The existing facilities, such as those in Portugal or Scotland, are all small and do not pose too much of an ecosystem problem.
On the other hand, to produce energy on a larger scale, facilities with a greater environmental impact are needed.
There are several possibilities: Ocean Power, for example, uses an interconnected buoy system.
The pulses generated by the waves that move the buoys up and down are converted into hydraulic pressure by the plungers and cylinders that are placed inside them.
The pressure drives a turbine, which powers a generator.
Electricity is carried to land by undersea cables.
There are currently four similar facilities in the planning stages, pending federal approval, and some of the energy produced would be used in a military facility.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, has already started generating power for a shopping mall and a parking lot with six underwater turbines in the East River estuary of New York.
When the water is in a current, the movement of the water turns the blades of the turbines, and this rotation feeds the generator.
Verdant said it has a long list of partners who are only waiting for the necessary permits to use the energy.
Wave after wave.
The opportunities offered by the tide are currently of particular interest.
Although it is a periodic phenomenon, tides are more predictable than wind, sun, or waves and are thus considered a more reliable source of energy.
New York, Maine, and Alaska, along with other coastal states, spent $7.5 million in 2008 to harness the energy provided by the tides, a figure that is expected to rise to $35 million in 2009.
